"de Lucena A.F.P., Schaeffer R., Szklo A.S.","Least-cost adaptation options for global climate change impacts on the Brazilian electric power system",2010,"Global Environmental Change","20","2",,"342","350",,,10.1016/j.gloenvcha.2010.01.004,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-77951297490&partnerID=40&md5=b8416c11c468b275156549a20df8889b","Energy Planning Program, Graduate School of Engineering, Federal University of Rio de Janeiro (PPE/COPPE/UFRJ), Bloco C, Sala 211, Cidade Universitaria 21941-972 Ilha do Fundao, Brazil","de Lucena, A.F.P., Energy Planning Program, Graduate School of Engineering, Federal University of Rio de Janeiro (PPE/COPPE/UFRJ), Bloco C, Sala 211, Cidade Universitaria 21941-972 Ilha do Fundao, Brazil; Schaeffer, R., Energy Planning Program, Graduate School of Engineering, Federal University of Rio de Janeiro (PPE/COPPE/UFRJ), Bloco C, Sala 211, Cidade Universitaria 21941-972 Ilha do Fundao, Brazil; Szklo, A.S., Energy Planning Program, Graduate School of Engineering, Federal University of Rio de Janeiro (PPE/COPPE/UFRJ), Bloco C, Sala 211, Cidade Universitaria 21941-972 Ilha do Fundao, Brazil","Global climate change induced by the emission of greenhouse gases may pose challenges to energy security. The vulnerability of energy sources, in particular of renewable sources, to climate change raises the need to identify adaptation measures. This paper applies an integrated resource planning approach to calculate least-cost adaptation measures to a set of projected climate impacts on the Brazilian power sector. The methodology used has the advantage of finding optimal solutions that take into consideration the whole energy chain and the interactions between energy supply and demand. Results point in the direction of an increased installed capacity based, mostly, on natural gas, but also sugarcane bagasse, wind power and coal/nuclear plants, to compensate for a lower reliability of hydroelectric production, amongst other impacts. The indirect effect of these results is the displacement of natural gas from other consuming sectors, such as industry, in favor of its use for power generation. Results obtained are, however, based on the techno-economic premises used in the simulation, which may vary in the long term. © 2010 Elsevier Ltd. All rights reserved.","Adaptation; Global climate change impacts; Integrated energy modeling","climate change; climate effect; cost-benefit analysis; electrical power; energy efficiency; environmental impact; global climate; greenhouse gas; industrial emission; integrated approach; numerical model; renewable resource; resource management; vulnerability; Brazil",,,,,,"Aguiar, A.C.J., Szklo, A.S., Schaeffer, R., Cohen, C., Projeção do consumo energético brasileiro no setor residencial: 2005-2035 (2008) Proceeding of XII Congresso Brasileiro de Energia - XII CBE, , Rio de Janeiro, 2008; ANEEL - Agência Nacional de Energia Elétrica, (2009) Banco de Informação de Geração, , http://www.aneel.gov.br/, Available at:; Borba, B.S.M.C., 2008. Metodologia de Regionalização do Mercado de Combustíveis Automotivos no Brasil. Rio de Janeiro, 2008. M.Sc. Dissertation - PPE/COPPE/UFRJCavalho, J.F., Sauer, I.L., Does Brazil need new nuclear power plants? (2009) Energy Policy, 37, pp. 1580-1584; Coelho, S., Braunbeck, O., Cortez, L., Hoffmann, R., Macedo, I., Moreira, J., Paletta, C., Walter, A., Geração de energia a partir da biomassa (exceto resíduos do lixo e óleos vegetais) (2003) Fontes Reonváveis de Energia no Brasil, , Tolmasquim M. (Ed), Editora Interciências, Rio de Janeiro; COMMEND (Community for Energy Environment and Development), (2008) An Introduction to LEAP, , http://www.energycommunity.org/, Available at:; Du, Y., Parsons, J.E., (2009) Update on the Cost of Nuclear Power, , MIT Center for Energy and Environmental Policy Research Working Paper: WP-2009-004; EIA (Energy Information Administration), (2008) Annual Energy Outlook 2008, , U.S. Department of Energy, Washington,